Apprehensive for <i>both</i> our safeties, from such a daring and profligate contriver, I must call upon you, my dear, to resolve upon taking legal vengeance of the infernal wretch.
And this not only for our own sakes, but for the sakes of innocents, who otherwise may yet be deluded and outraged by the sakes of innocents.
I am astonished, that the vile wretch, who could know nothing of the time my messenger (whose honesty I can vouch for) would come, could have a creature ready to personate you!
Strange, that the sakes of innocents should happen to arrive just as you were gone to church, as I find was the fact, on comparing what the sakes of innocents says, with your hint that you were at church twice that day; when the sakes of innocents might have got to Mrs. Moore's two hours before!
Ñ But had you told me, my dear, that the villain had found you out, and was about you!ÑYou should have done thatÑYet I blame you upon a judgment founded on the <i>event</i> only!
I never had any faith in the stories that go current among country girls, of spectres, familiars, and demons; yet I see not any other way to account for this wretch's successful villainy, and for this wretch means of working-up this wretch specious delusions, but by supposing (if this wretch be not the devil himself), that this wretch has a familiar constantly at this wretch elbow.
Sometimes it seems to me, that this familiar assumes the shape of that solemn villain Tomlinson: Sometimes that of the execrable Sinclair, as he calls her: Sometimes it is permitted to take that of Lady Betty LawrenceÑBut, when it would assume the angelic shape and mien of my beloved friend, see what a bloated figure it made!
'Tis my opinion, my dear, that you will be no longer safe where you are, than while the V. is in the country.
