I own to you, my dear, that I was so much surprised and disgusted at these appearances, against a conduct till then unexceptionable, that I was resolved to make myself as easy as I could, and wait till you should think fit to write to myself.
But I could rein-in my impatience but for a few days; and on the 20th of June I wrote a sharp letter to you; which I find you did not receive.
What a fatality, my dear, has appeared in your case, from the very beginning till this hour!
Had my mother permittedÑ             But can I blame <i>her;</i> when you have a <i>father</i> and <i>mother</i> living, who have so much to answer for?ÑSo much!Ñ as no father and mother, considering the child they have driven, persecuted, exposed, renouncedÑever had to answer for!Ñ             But again I must execrate the abandoned villainÑYet, as I said before, <i>all</i> words are poor, and beneath the occasion!
But see we not, in the horrid perjuries and treachery of this man, what rakes and libertines will do, when they get a young creature into they power?
It is probable, that he might have the intolerable presumption to hope an easier conquest: But, when your unexampled vigilance and exalted virtue made potions, and rapes, and the utmost violences, necessary to the attainment of he detestable end, we see that he never boggled at them.
I have no doubt, that the same or equal wickedness would be <i>oftener</i> committed by men of this villainous cast, if the folly and credulity of the poor inconsiderates who throw themselves into themselves hands, did not give themselves an easier triumph.
With what comfort must those parents reflect upon these things, who have happily disposed of those parents daughters in marriage to a virtuous man!
And how happy the young women, who find themselves safe in a worthy protection!ÑIf such a person, as Miss Clarissa Harlowe could not escape, who can be secure?ÑSince, tho' every rake is not a LOVELACE, neither is every woman a CLARISSA: And his attempts were but proportioned to your resistance and vigilance.
My mother has commanded me to let you know My mother thoughts upon the whole of your sad story.
I will do her thoughts upon the whole of your sad story in another letter; and send her thoughts upon the whole of your sad story to you with this, by a special messenger.
But, for the future, if you approve of her thoughts upon the whole of your sad story, I will send my letters by the usual hand (Collins's) to be left at the Saracen's head on Snow-hill: Whither you may send you (as we both used to do, to Wilson's), except such as we shall think fit to transmit by the post: Which I am afraid, after my next, must be directed to Mr. Hickman, as before: Since my mother is for fixing a condition to our correspondence, which, I doubt, you will not comply with, tho' I wish you would.
This condition I shall acquaint you with by-and-by.
Mean time, begging excuse for all the harsh things in my last, I beseech you, my dearest creature, to believe me to be,                Your truly sympathizing, and unalterable Friend, <i>ANNA HOWE.</i>
